<br>
<br>
With us now are Canadian defense attorney John Conroy. And we also have radio talk show host, Michael Medved.<br>
       Gentlemen, I’d like to welcome both of you...<br>
       MICHAEL MEDVED, RADIO TALK SHOW HOST: Thank you.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: ... to our show. Let me begin with you, Michael. America, obviously, has shared a relatively open border with Canada throughout our history. And we’ve done so because we’ve shared Canada’s values throughout the history.<br>
       Why do you think there’s been a bit of a jump to the left, being very gracious about it, lately? <br>
       In Canada?<br>
       MEDVED: Well, actually, you’re forgetting, Joe, about the two times that we invaded Canada. And, alas, we didn’t win and capture the country, which would have been better for everybody.<br>
       But the point about that-we did, in the War of 1812 and in the Revolution.<br>
       But the problem with Canada-it’s a great illustration of something you were talking about before. Canada, in the last 20 years, has had virtually unlimited immigration. And there are now 17 percent of Canadians who are foreign born. That compares to 11 percent in the United States.<br>
       The result of that is all standards breaking down, all traditions breaking down. The fact that it’s not even considered a united country anymore. It’s also been a living laboratory of bilingualism.<br>
       You have this entire obsession with Quebec and the different way, and everything has to be in English and French.<br>
       What a good illustration for Yankees, for Americans, about why we can’t move at all in that direction by, for instance, making Spanish an official language in the United States.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: John Conroy, a lot of Americans are obviously concerned, not in Florida, but along the northern border, that what-or Canada’s problems essentially become America’s problems sooner or later.<br>
       Do you understand why some Americans are concerned about the legalization of drugs and some of the other social trends that are starting to take shape in Canada, and taking root in their political system?<br>
       JOHN CONROY, CANADIAN DEFENSE ATTORNEY: Well, I understand why some Americans feel that way. Usually they’re fundamentalist, right-wing people. They’re non-liberal and they don’t understand very much about Canada.<br>
       A lot of what I could just barely hear a few minutes ago sounded like somebody who’s never really taken the trouble to find out what really is going on in Canada.<br>
       MEDVED: Wait, wait. I’ve hitchhiked along the entire TransCanada Highway. I’ve spoken and lectured in every major city in Canada and...<br>
       CONROY: What year did you do that?<br>
       MEDVED: Well, I did that actually in the 1970s.<br>
       CONROY: Right. Well, in 1982, we got a constitution called the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.<br>
       MEDVED: Yes, I’m well aware of it.<br>
       CONROY: And that constitution is what’s responsible for a lot of the changes in Canada that you’re complaining about.<br>
       (CROSSTALK)<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Hold it one second. Mr. Conroy, you just blamed-and you sound like an American politician blaming a lot of things...<br>
       CONROY: I can’t hear you.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: ... on fundamentalist Christians. But the fact is that there are a lot of people who aren’t even Christians at all who would be concerned about heroine safe houses and the legalization of marijuana.<br>
       CONROY: Yes, but you’ve been going down the road of putting everybody in prison for that sort of thing, so you have over two million people in prison, and you still have the nerve to call yourselves the land of the free.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Which is why we...<br>
       CONROY: We’ve gone-we’ve looked at your road, and we’ve said, look at the road they’re going down.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Oh, my God! <br>
       CONROY: We don’t want to put all our people in prison. It doesn’t work your way, so we’re looking at a different way.<br>
       (CROSSTALK)<br>
       CONROY: ... instead of creating more harm.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Hold on. Michael Medved, go ahead and respond to that. <br>
       Is ...<br>
       MEDVED: Which is why we...<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: ... America really no longer the land of the free?<br>
       MEDVED: No, America is a land where a more sane criminal justice system has actually caused a reduction over the last 20 years in the crime rate, where in Canada the crime rate has gone up. The economy...<br>
       CONROY: I don’t know where you get your facts from.<br>
       MEDVED: Well, I know...<br>
       (CROSSTALK)<br>
       MEDVED: Toronto historically was a wonderfully safe city, and there’s a huge epidemic of crime in Toronto, is there not?<br>
       CONROY: No. I don’t think there’s an epidemic of crime in Canada whatsoever. We’re actually making very good progress in the crime department compared to you.<br>
       I mean, you have...<br>
       MEDVED: And which is why your dollar is so strong?<br>
       CONROY: ... you know, you kill more people with your guns than any other country in the world.<br>
       And even though we have more guns, we don’t have the same levels of violent crime that you do.<br>
       But, and, you know, let’s talk about the marijuana thing...<br>
       (CROSSTALK)<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Hold on a second.<br>
       CONROY: ... for a minute.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Well, we don’t have the minute, unfortunately.<br>
       CONROY: All that we’re doing is playing catch-up to you. You’ve had all these states that have these traffic ticket systems ...<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: OK.<br>
       CONROY: ... since back in the ’60s and ’70s. All our government is proposing to do is something similar. We don’t think tha...<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: OK, we’re just...<br>
       CONROY: ... they’re going far enough.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: ... OK...<br>
       CONROY: We put our faith in the courts.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: Listen, cut him off for a second. Michael Medved, I’m going to give you 15 seconds to wrap it up, and then we got to go. The guy should run for Senate in America.<br>
       MEDVED: Well, look-or for Parliament.<br>
       The other illustration that Canada has is that it shows why the two party system is so important and worth preserving in the United States. There isn’t a united, effective conservative party in Canada anymore. <br>
       There used to be once upon a time. That fell apart. And...<br>
       CONROY: Because they’re so extreme.<br>
       MEDVED: ... it’s damaged the whole country. I feel sorry for them.<br>
       SCARBOROUGH: OK, gentlemen. I’m sorry, we got to go. But you two have to come back next week and continue this debate, because I’ll guarantee you it’s a debate that’s going to be going on for some time in the land of the free-Canada-and in the land of the oppressed-the United States of America.<br>
       Coming up on SCARBOROUGH COUNTRY, we got the buzz.<br>
       And later, a Midwest judge gives a green light to sex offenders to hang around in public areas where kids swing. There you go again.<br>
